INSERT INTO `article` VALUES (3,'The final countdown to the 2010 Oscars has begun, with The Hurt Locker and Avatar going head-to-head for the coveted best picture award.\r\nJames Cameron\'s 3D sci-fi juggernaut, which has taken more than $2bn (&pound;1.32bn) at the box office, had looked like a favourite in early 2010.',NULL,'The final countdown to the 2010 Oscars has begun, with The Hurt Locker and Avatar going head-to-head for the coveted best picture award.\r\nJames Cameron\'s 3D sci-fi juggernaut, which has taken more than $2bn (&pound;1.32bn) at the box office, had looked like a favourite in early 2010.\r\nBut his ex-wife Kathryn Bigelow\'s Iraq bomb disposal drama is now being tipped in Tinseltown to take the prize.\r\nBoth lead the way at Sunday\'s Academy Awards with nine nominations each.\r\nIf the Hurt Locker wins, it will be the lowest-grossing best picture winner in Oscars history with earnings of around $15m (&pound;9.9m).\r\nBut with 10 films in the running for best picture and a change in the voting system, the way is still open for a major Oscar upset.\r\nQuentin Tarantino\'s eight times nominated World War II fantasy Inglourious Basterds could benefit from a split vote.\r\nBritish hopes\r\nCameron and Bigelow also go against each other in the best director category with Bigelow heavily tipped to win.\r\nIndustry paper The Hollywood Reporter on Friday predicted wins for Bigelow for both best picture and director.\r\nIf Bigelow is named best director she would be first female to win - only four women have ever been nominated.\r\n\r\nSandra Bullock is expected to win best actress for The Blind Side\r\nJeff Bridges is widely expected to take best actor for Crazy Heart.\r\nThe 60-year-old has swept the awards season this year, winning Golden Globe and Screen Actors Guild Awards for his portrayal of an alcoholic country singer.\r\nBritish hopes in the acting categories include Colin Firth, Dame Helen Mirren and Carey Mulligan.\r\nFirth, up against Bridges for his Bafta-winning performance in A Single Man told the BBC he did not expect to be making an Oscar speech.\r\n&quot;I\'m not sure I\'ll get the chance. I think I might have peaked,&quot; he admitted at the Independent Spirit Awards on Friday.\r\nLikewise, Sandra Bullock is expected to win best actress for American football drama The Blind Side.\r\nBut she has close competition from Meryl Streep, whose role in Julie and Julia has earned her a record 16th Oscar nomination.\r\nShe is also up against Carey Mulligan, whose Bafta win for An Education raised her profile in the final few days of voting.\r\n\'Christmas for movies\'\r\nMeanwhile Dame Helen Mirren, nominated for The Last Station, told the BBC she was not too nervous ahead of the big night.\r\n&quot;The first time is so frightening and intimidating, but once you\'ve done it once you know the nature of the beast,&quot; she said. &quot;But they do it incredibly well here in America. It is the great celebration of film - it\'s like Christmas for movies.&quot;\r\n\r\n*Wallace and Gromit creator Nick Park is hoping to win a fifth Oscar*\r\nThe best supporting actor and actress awards seem to be already in the bag for Christoph Waltz (Inglourious Basterds) and Mo\'Nique (Precious).\r\nAll of which leaves stop motion animation heroes Wallace and Gromit as one of Britain\'s best hopes of taking home an Oscar.\r\nNick Park, nominated in the short animated film category for A Matter Of Loaf And Death, is in line to win his fifth golden statuette.\r\nHe said: &quot;What\'s really difficult is I\'ve read that Wallace and Gomit is favourite but you can\'t afford in yourself to get too confident, and you\'ve got to imagine things not working out so you enjoy the evening.\r\n&quot;But obviously with four already, I won\'t be that disappointed.&quot;','Hurt Locker in final sprint to win Oscar race'),(4,'Makers of small web browsers want their programs to be given more prominence on Microsoft\'s browser choice screen.\r\nSix software firms have complained to the EU saying many do not realise their programs were on offer.\r\nTo see all 12 web browsers, users must scroll to the right when viewing Microsoft\'s ballot screen.\r\nThe choice is being offered as part of a settlement of an anti-trust case brought against Microsoft by the European Commission.',NULL,'Makers of small web browsers want their programs to be given more prominence on Microsoft\'s browser choice screen.\r\nSix software firms have complained to the EU saying many do not realise their programs were on offer.\r\nTo see all 12 web browsers, users must scroll to the right when viewing Microsoft\'s ballot screen.\r\nThe choice is being offered as part of a settlement of an anti-trust case brought against Microsoft by the European Commission.\r\n*Global choice*\r\n&quot;The final choice screen design leaves the vast majority of users unaware that there are more than five browsers to choose from,&quot; the six firms said in their petition.\r\n	\r\n*BROWSER CHOICES*\r\n* Avant\r\n* Chrome\r\n* Firefox\r\n* Flock\r\n* Green Browser\r\n* Internet Explorer\r\n* K-meleon\r\n* Maxthon\r\n* Opera\r\n* Safari\r\n* Sleipnir\r\n* Slim\r\nThe petition is signed by the makers of the Avant, Flock, Maxthon, Slim, Sleipnir and Green browsers. The makers of the other browser on offer, K-Meleon, did not sign it.\r\nFrom 1 March, the browser choice have been popping up on the screens of millions of Europeans who have Internet Explorer as their default web browser.\r\nThe browser choice screen is designed as a single panel. Scrolling to the right reveals all twelve browsers on offer.\r\n&quot;We are only requesting the simple addition of any text or design element, that would indicate to an average user that there are choices \'to the right of the visible screen\',&quot; said the petition.\r\nMicrosoft said that the browser choice screen was drawn up to be compliant with the deal agreed with the European Commission.\r\nEarly reports suggest the browser choice screen is leading to a rise in the numbers of people trying browsers other than Internet Explorer.\r\nIn a statement, Opera said it had seen downloads of its browser increase threefold since the choice screen system started rolling out.\r\nAt the same time, the European Committee for Interoperable Systems (ECIS) has asked for the browser choice system to be repeated around the world.\r\nIn a statement it called on &quot;competition agencies around the world to give their consumers the benefit of browser choice, which will spur competition and improve the Web experience for all&quot;.\r\nSo far, the ECIS campaign has got no further than an open letter on the organisation\'s site. However, it did not rule out a more active campaign on the issue of browser choice.\r\nECIS members include long-time Microsoft rivals Oracle, IBM, Red Hat, Opera and Adobe.','Browser makers demand screen time'),(6,'The kind of meditation taught at Kagyu Samye Dzong London is called Calm Abiding meditation or Shinay in Tibetan. As the name suggests the aim of this meditation is to achieve a state of tranquillity, and then abide within this state. Learning to meditate is deeply rewarding. It is a simple life skill that can help us make the most of everyday. ',15,'The kind of meditation taught at Kagyu Samye Dzong London is called Calm Abiding meditation or Shinay in Tibetan. As the name suggests the aim of this meditation is to achieve a state of tranquillity, and then abide within this state. Learning to meditate is deeply rewarding. It is a simple life skill that can help us make the most of everyday. The insights and experiences that arise naturally from within us can enrich our lives and improve our wellbeing. Being able to calm our mind and experience a little mental peace after an upsetting experience is a profound way to restore our balance and cope with the situation.  \"We use things as tools for our own benefit. But today it is often the other way around: Things use us. They rule our way of life. But when we are no longer their masters, we cannot use them to our benefit. Our lives today are very fast and complex and full of potential stress and conflict. If in that situation we cannot maintain our inner peace and clear mind we can lose our mental stability and that will lead to mental conflicts and illness. Under these circumstances today more then ever meditation is especially helpful and important.\" (From an interview with Gyalwa Karmapa Urgyen Trinley Dorje in Gyuto India June 2006)\r\n\r\n[shi ney meditation](image)\r\n\r\nIn our classes and courses you\'ll learn different techniques for settling your mind. The Classes are taken by experienced meditators in a friendly and informal atmosphere. You can then attend our open meditation sessions held each week at the Centre and practice the exercises you\'ve been taught.','Meditation'),(8,'Buddha means awakened one, it was the name given to a historical figure bone into an Indian royal family about 625BC. As a talented prince called Siddartha he lived a life of ease and splendor, but was never able to satisfy a deep craving for a meaningful spiritual life. So he left the palace and headed into the forests around Bodhi Gaya. Spending many years seaching for teachers and meditation practises that would bring a release from birth aging sickness death and again birth, he finally settled under the bodhi tree. It was this final meditation which brought to this wandering prince the awakening that earned him his title of Buddha.',6,'The Kagyu tradition is one of the four main schools of Tibetan Buddhism. It is reknowned for its emphasis on meditation as embodied by such great masters as Marpa, Milarepa and Gampopa, whose example inspired people throughout Tibet.\r\n\r\nThe supreme head of the Kagyu lineage is the Karmapa\r\n\r\n[KarmapaWalking](image)\r\n\r\nThe Karmapas have been the supreme heads of the Kagyu lineage of Tibetan Buddhism since the first Karmapa, Dusum Khyenpa, in the 12th century. Historically, Dusum Khyenpa was the first Lama recognised to intentionally reincarnate as a particular master.\r\n\r\nIn all of his successive incarnations, the Karmapa has served as the primary source of refuge for all the followers of the Karma Kagyu Lineage. As the central teacher of the Kagyu lineage, he ensures that the teachings are transmitted in their entirety and preserved for future generations. The Karmapa is an extraordinary individual, whose life itself may be seen as a profound teaching. He clearly manifests the potential inherent in all living beings to fully develop the qualities of perfect wisdom, unconditional love and all-pervasive compassion.\r\n\r\nHis Holiness the 17th Gyalwa Karmapa, Orgyen Trinley Dorje, has been living at Tsurphu monastery in Tibet since his enthronement in 1992. In January 2000 he arrived in Dharamsala, India, the main seat of the Dalai Lama in exile, after fleeing over the mountains with a small group of attendants. His arrival has brought great joy to his followers worldwide, who are now able to receive his teachings, guidance and blessings.','Buddhism'),(28,'There are so many different ways to make a meaningful connection to the Centre, to the people who share its life and benefit from it\'s presence.',8,'Come and join our growing team of volunteers who have already started to renovate our new building. We have bought a grade 2 listed building which will become our permanent London centre. The building is substantially bigger than our current Manor Place centre and will require considerable renovation. More inforation here\r\n\r\nWe are looking for volunteers who can commit for a length of time and we are especially keen to recruit those skilled in general building skills, painting and decorating, electrical work, plumbing, plastering, and cooking.\r\n\r\nWe will have a limited amount of residential accommodation available, free-of-charge, for volunteers. If you are interested please contact the Kagyu Samye Dzong office for more details and to discuss these opportunities informally.\r\n\r\nPlease note: there are also opportunities for occasional and weekend volunteers, but please note the minimum daily time commitment is four hours.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe Former Bermondsey Library, Spa Road, London Kagyu Samye Dzong London\r\n33 Manor Place\r\nLondon\r\nSE17 3BD\r\n\r\ntel: +44 (0)20 7708 8969\r\nemail: manorplace@samye.org','Community'),(29,'The Centre offers a wealth of complementary healthcare from qualified practitioners. Each week the community clinic offers a range of treatments at very competitive rates.',16,'Community Clinic: Therapies offered\r\nHolistic massage with Lise-Marie Lejamtel\r\n\r\nI worked for a number of years in a caring capacity where I became aware of the benefits of a caring touch. Massage doesn\'t only have physiological effects such as muscle tension release, better regeneration of the cells, improved circulation or better skin tone and colour through removal of dead cells. It can also bring out a wonderful sense of mental relaxation, soothing and comfort. In the long term it improves body image, awareness and general self-esteem.\r\n\r\nI qualified and insured as a holistic massage therapist and offer part or full-body massage, using oil on the skin. The body is fully covered with towels, except the part that is worked on. Techniques include effleurage, manipulation of the muscles, compressive and kneading movements, light percussions and lymphatic drainage movements. The client is encouraged to give feed-back during the massage so that I can adapt the pressure and focus where it is needed.\r\n\r\nThe first session always starts with a consultation to check the suitability of the treatment. If you have contra-indications, I may need you to ask an authorization from your doctor prior to the treatment.\r\n\r\nLooking forward to hearing from you!\r\n\r\nLise-Marie Lejamtel ITEC CthA\r\n(t) 07906 362006\r\n(e) lisemarie.lejamtel@gmail.com\r\nAcupressure Massage and Relexology with Karin Summers\r\n\r\nOriginally from a science background (Cancer Research), with an Applied Biology Degree, I started my training as a massage therapist about 6 years ago. After learning the basics of Holistic massage and Anatomy and Physiology, I studied Reflexology which I found an extremely effective methodology. Prompted by a desire to be able to give effective treatments to all sorts of people in all sorts of circumstances, I went on to study sports massage which gave me a more in depth knowledge and seated acupressure chair massage.\r\n\r\nThe Acupressure seated massage I perform is derived from the Traditional Japanese massage (AMMA), introduced by David Palmer, an american, in the eighties. He first instigated the, now familiar, portable massage chair and marketed this effective and accessible style of treatment to the western world. This therapy, in which the client remains fully clothed, provides an invigorating boost and is deeply relaxing. Deep pressure is applied to over 150 acupressure points over the neck, back, shoulders and arms, stimulating the proper flow of energy throughout the body systems.\r\nCranio Sacral Therapy with Frederick Maitland\r\n\r\nI have been practicing Cranio Sacral Therapy since 1999. I have trained and assisted with the Milne Institute\'s Visionary CranioSacral Work program, both in the United States and Italy. I have also studied with the Upledger Institute, and the Biodynamics of Charles Ridley. I am a full member of the CranioSacral Therapy Association of the United Kingdom.\r\n\r\nAs well as my CranioSacral Therapy qualifications, I graduated with a Doctor of Chiropractic degree in the United States. I have also received trainings from a number of Native American teachers, particularly Dr Leslie Grey, of the Woodfish Institute, San Francisco, California.\r\n\r\nWhat I love about CranioSacral, is how subtle and profound it is, mirroring our true inborn capacity for health and healing. I greatly enjoy working with people of all ages, and am fascinated by each person\'s life story and experiences. I am inspired both by my teachers, and the masters I have met on my travels. Yet it is within the deep stillness of Nature that I find the heart of my practice.\r\n\r\nPlease do not hesitate to contact me with further questions and/or to book your sessions.\r\n\r\nFrederick Maitland RCST 0787 551 8069 info@stoneriver.org\r\n\r\nHow to find Kagyu Samye Dzong London ','Community Clinic'),(30,'Kagyu Samye Dzong London will soon be taking up residence in a new building. For the foreseeable future 33 Manor Place will remain open. Meanwhile work is underway at 15 Spa Road. What will this new building bring to London? We hope everyone will find something helpful in our new diverse Centre.',24,'Kagyu Samye Dzong London will soon be taking up residence in a new building. For the foreseeable future 33 Manor Place will remain open. Meanwhile work is underway at 15 Spa Road. What will this new building bring to London? We hope everyone will find something helpful in our new diverse Centre.\r\n\r\nh3. Learn to meditate\r\n\r\nFor those wanting to learn and practice meditation there will be two beautiful meditation halls decorated in the Tibetan style. Weekly classes led by experienced teachers will introduce the basic principles of meditation and help to get you started. Each week you can come and meditate at the Centre either when the meditation halls are not being used, or during one of our regular group meditation sessions.\r\n\r\nh3. Practice Buddhism\r\n\r\nEach month traditional Buddhist practices for well being, health and world peace are completed by the resident ordained and lay community. You can join in with these prayers and group meditations. Texts are available in the shop and courses explaining the practices occur regularly throughout the year.\r\n\r\n\r\nh3. Spa Road Renovation\r\n\r\nh4. Find peace and well being\r\n\r\nWe will once again create a tea room. The tea room has been greatly missed by regular users of the Centre since our departure from the Carlisle Lane Centre, but in Spa Road there will be a space to relax with friends. Spend time in the Tea room winding down before a therapy treatment or meditation class.\r\n\r\nh4. Health treatments\r\n\r\nMany people rely on the Centre to provide quality health treatments. We will hold monthly clinics by a Tibetan doctor, who uses traditional Tibetan methods and medicines to treat a wide variety of ailments. At Spa Road we have a suite of treatment rooms, and larger spaces for group activities such as Pregnancy Yoga, Martial Arts, and psychotherapy courses, conferences and much more. The Centre will provide the space for a weekly Community Clinic which will offer many alternative treatments by professional practitioners at a low cost. Treatments such as Acupuncture, Cranio Sacral, Homeopathey, Reflexology, Shiastsu, Indian Head Massage and much more will be available weekly during the daytime.\r\n\r\nh4. Volunteer at the Centre\r\n\r\nKagyu Samye Dzong London is run by volunteers. Volunteering at the Centre is a great way to get to know the Centre better and become a part of the community. You may have particular skills that you&rsquo;d like to offer, or maybe you can commit to a rota and help in the shop or office each week. The Centre is always on the look out for cooks, and there is the never ending job of keeping the building clean and tidy. Look out for our volunteer days at 15 Spa Road and join in.','Spa Road'),(31,'A member of the London Samye Dzong community volunteer\'s for a scientific research project. Allowing an fMRI scaner watch while they meditate.',NULL,'Tashi Zangpo, the monk at Kagyu Samye Dzong London Tibetan Buddhist Centre, asked me if I was going to take part in a piece of research on meditation and the brain. It was the first I had heard of Dr Elena Antonova\'s project based in King\'s College London. She was looking for people with 7 years or more experience of meditation, who were right handed, between 18 & 65 and had no metal in the body. I got in touch.\r\n\r\n[fMRI Scanner](image)\r\n\r\nAfter filling in a form and booking an afternoon off work I was all set for my first fMRI brain scan. This is the first piece of UK based research of this kind. Using \'Functional Magnetic Resonance Imaging (fMRI) to scan the brain activity of people meditating was something pioneered at MIT (Massachusetts Institute of Technology) in response to the Dalia Lama\'s \'Mind and Life\' summits during the early nineties, this is an area of science that has been deeply influenced by Buddhist mediators.\r\n\r\nDr Anotonova\'s research is very exciting. Mindfulness-based Cognitive Therapy (MBCT) has already been proven as highly effective for treating mental disorders like bipolar or depression. By completing this research she is hoping to establish objective outcome measures, this would ground MBCT as an evidence-based medicine, which could then be made more widely available for patients on the NHS. Imagine a treatment plan for metal illness that did not rely on medication, but on mindfulness.\r\n\r\nI felt nervous leading up to my appointment. I began to question my practice, have I been doing it correctly? What if nothing shows up on the scan, I\'d feel a bit of a fraud. I guess this is the whole point of the research, to find ways to verify a subjective experience and reassure people they are doing something to their brains when they meditate. So to prepare myself for the experience I did a few sessions laying on by back in my room, meditating with my head in a bucket. I know this is something that hospital staff do with children before they have an MRI scan, they have them lay down in a play tunnel and talk to them about what it will be like. After this I felt much more relaxed about the day, and gave myself more room to be excited and curious.\r\n\r\nI arrived at the Centre for Neuroimaging Sciences and was quickly signing forms and chatting to Dr Anotonova. She explained the three types of mind modes that she wanted to measure, and I had a 20 minute practice moving at random between; \'Mind Wandering\' which was a grasping, monkey mind mode. \'Future Planning\' which is like comtemplation or period of directed thought, and \'Mindfulness\' which is open awareness, objectless Shiney meditation, or mediation on the present moment. We entered a locker area and de-metaled by removing all metallic objects from our persons. Then into the scanning room, and before I knew it I was flat on my back with my head inside a very heavy, very expensive machine.\r\n\r\nI had to lay really still for an initial scan. The scanner startled me as is clunked into life making strange and loud noises, I felt like a frightened little bardo being crushed by the elements. I\'m sure the heart rate monitor shows a peak during the first few minutes. Still the sequences began and during the first \'Mindfullness\' period I felt much better, I relaxed and even started to enjoy the experience. My preparation with the bucket would have been much more realistic had I been putting my head in a bass speaker. Then the time and money ran out, each scan costs just short of &amp;amp;pound;500, and I was wandering back to Manor Place.\r\n\r\nI was very impressed with Dr Antonova\'s commitment and passion for her subject. She is a keen meditator in the Dzogchen tradition, and has great plans for further research. Opportunities to get involved and join a research programme will come up again. Its so meaningful, meditation is such a gift, such a healthy practice, anyone can learn and its something the Buddhadharma explains so fully. How wonderful to support it\'s integration into science and healthcare. If you are interested in supporting Elena\'s work either as a subject to study or financially then get in touch.\r\n\r\n\r\nDr Elena Antonova\r\n\r\nBox PO62, Department of Psychological Medicine\r\nInstitute of Psychiatry\r\nKing\'s College London\r\nCutcombe Road\r\nLondon, SE5 9RG','Mindfulness, Magnets and the NHS'),(32,'Early information about the arrival of 1,000 Buddha statues coming from Tibet.',31,'h2. Sept 09 - 1,000 Buddhas from Tibet coming to Bermonsey South London\r\n\r\nBuddhists in Bermondsey\'s old public library are working hard on an unusual restoration project. Having taken over an old building used by the council they are busy removing the artificial artex ceilings and false walls. Meanwhile great efforts are being made far away, over the Himalayas, in the troubled region of Tibet. For thousands of years Buddhists have created statues of the original Buddha to aid them in their meditations, and create special places of harmony and healing. It was a common practice in India, Asia, China and Tibet to create 1,000 such statues and have them all collected together in one meditation hall. The effect is quite overwhelming having 1,000 pairs of eyes gazing at you from a mass of guilded gold. Space is being created now for such a collection of 1,000 Buddha\'s in Bermondsey\'s new Buddhist Centre - Kagyu Samye Dzong London.\r\n\r\n\r\nLondon\'s assembly of 1,000 Buddhas are being produced in eastern Tibet in a series of local foundries. Once the statues have been cast and cleaned the hollow shell will be filled with precious substances and mantras. Its a huge task. So why go to all this trouble? Since it is not possible to just buy 1,000 Buddha statues from UK suppliers it is necessary to source them from the sites at which these Buddha\'s are actually made. Once they have arrived in England they will form the backdrop to three other large statues which are being sculpted on-site by Tibetan artist Lama Thubten.\r\n\r\n\r\nh2. London\'s peace zones?\r\n\r\n\r\nCould you find a quiet corner in a park, or on the grand canal? May be at the back of an old church, or in a private square. How might you go about creating a peaceful place? Buddhists in Bermonsey are going to extreme lengths to create a meditation hall which will open to the public next year. Imagine 1,000 Buddha statues in a posture of mental and physical harmony watching over you as you try to calm your mind and feel the stillness that lies within. Sound intimidating? It was a common practice in India, Asia, China and Tibet to create 1,000 such statues and have them all collected together in one meditation hall. Buddhists believe that actions performed in the presence of even a single statue of the Buddha have the same power and effect as actions performed in front of an actual living enlighten being. So one wish made in the presence of 1,000 Buddhas becomes a powerful prayer multiplied a thousand times.\r\n\r\nKagyu Samye Dzong London has been carrying out its work in London for the past 12 years under the guidance of Lama Zangmo, a Buddhist nun with over 12 years of meditation retreat behind her. She has a team of dedicated volunteers transforming the old public library on Spa road in Bermonsey. When completed this 19th century building will become home for the cities largest Buddhist Centre.  ','1,000 Buddhas 2,000 Eyes'),(34,'testsetsetset set ',7,'asdf asdf asd asd fasd asdf fasd asd f','test article'),(35,'Lama Thubten explains his belief that Buddhist art can bring benefit\r\nto people in the West;&amp;quot;...if one seeks the deeper meaning behind the\r\nstatues and follows the path of the Buddha, then one will never have\r\nto face disappointment.&amp;quot;',23,'TRADITIONAL TIBETAN ART COMES TO SOUTH LONDON\r\n\r\nTibetan Lama and master craftsman brings the Buddha to Bermondsey\r\n\r\nSometimes he fondly remembers his nomadic childhood in Tibet but for\r\nnow Lama Thubten Kunsal is very happy to be thousands of miles away,\r\nboth geographically and culturally, in Bermondsey, south-east London\r\nwhere he is creating traditional Buddhist sculptures and other artwork\r\nfor a soon-to-open Tibetan Buddhist centre.  The centre will be a\r\nplace of tranquillity, meditation and health open to everyone.\r\n\r\nProdigiously talented from a young age, Lama Thubten trained under\r\nsome of Tibet&amp;amp;rsquo;s greatest Buddhist artists and teachers. At the age of\r\n22 he joined Tashi Kelsang Darkeling monastery where he continued to\r\nstudy traditional Tibetan art while undertaking intensive Buddhist\r\npractice.\r\n\r\nIn 2002 he journeyed from Tibet via China to Kagyu Samye Ling\r\nmonastery in Scotland at the invitation of the founder, Choje Akong\r\nTulku Rinpoche, who was aware of his compatriot&amp;amp;rsquo;s great talent. At\r\nSamye Ling, Lama Thubten set to work crafting a number of beautiful\r\nstatues in the shrine-rooms and grounds of the monastery.\r\n\r\n!lama thubten!\r\n\r\nIn 2009 the London branch of the monastery, Kagyu Samye Dzong,\r\nacquired the old Bermondsey Library, and a volunteer workforce has\r\nbeen busy renovating it to create the largest Tibetan Buddhist centre\r\nin London. Lama Thubten has been there since November creating a\r\nnumber of major sculptures including the 2.5m-high Buddha statue which\r\nwill be the centrepiece of the main shrine-room.  The official opening\r\nof the centre will be in June 2010 and will be performed by His\r\nHoliness 17th Karmapa, head of the Karma Kagyu Buddhist tradition,\r\nduring his first visit to Europe.\r\n\r\nLama Thubten explains his belief that Buddhist art can bring benefit\r\nto people in the West; &amp;amp;ldquo;...if one seeks the deeper meaning behind the\r\nstatues and follows the path of the Buddha, then one will never have\r\nto face disappointment.&amp;amp;rdquo;\r\n\r\nKagyu Samye Dzong London, Tibetan Buddhist centre for world peace and\r\nhealth was founded in 1998 and is under the daily guidance of Lama\r\nZangmo.\r\n\r\nNOTES FOR EDITORS\r\n\r\n   1. Kagyu Samye Dzong London is a branch of Kagyu Samye Ling\r\nMonastery in Scotland, a Buddhist Centre which was established in 1967\r\nand now has branches worldwide. The London centre is directed on a day\r\nto day basis by Lama Zangmo.\r\n   2. The director of the centre, Lama Zangmo, first became a\r\npracticing Buddhist in 1977. She entered a four-year closed retreat in\r\n1984, during which time she became ordained as a Buddhist nun. Lama\r\nZangmo went on to spend eleven and a half years in retreat. Following\r\nthat training she became the first director of Kagyu Samye Dzong\r\nLondon, on its foundation in 1998. In recognition of her long\r\nexperience she was honoured with the title of Lama in 2001.\r\n   3. The Karmapas have been the supreme heads of the Kagyu lineage of\r\nTibetan Buddhism since the first Karmapa Dusum Khyenpa in the 12th\r\ncentury. The current (17th) Karmapa is 24 year old Orgyen Trinley\r\nDorje,  born in Kham, Tibet. In January 2000 he arrived in Dharamsala,\r\nIndia, the seat of the Dalai Lama in exile. He now resides at nearby\r\nGyuto monastery. In 2008 he made his first visit to the West with a\r\nsuccessful 3 week tour of the US. He will undertake his first European\r\ntour in May/June 2010, visiting 10 countries including England &amp;amp;amp;\r\nScotland.\r\n\r\n Contact:\r\n\r\nKagyu Samye Dzong London\r\n33 Manor Place\r\nLondon SE17 3BD\r\n0207 708 8969\r\nwww.london.samye.org ','TRADITIONAL TIBETAN ART COMES TO SOUTH LONDON'),(36,'The Centre needs people who can focus on tasks and get them done, and also really take pride in what they do, that&rsquo;s very important.',24,'Hi I&rsquo;m Phil, I&rsquo;m a volunteer here at Spa Road. When I first arrived it was in the back of my mind that this kind of project, in this case a building project, related to spiritual practice means that you are going to be engaging with things, possibly that you wouldn&rsquo;t be if it was a normal commercial project. I think it&rsquo;s to do with the fact that in a sense its not just a building it is a place that will be offered to the general public a place to practice, in this case in the Tibetan Buddhist Tradition. On the one hand you can see it in a very logical down to earth way, it&rsquo;s a building project. But on another level its activating all the energies and stirring up all the things that are opposing a project like this. In an individual&rsquo;s life its&rsquo; bringing these things to the surface as much as anything else, so I think in a strange way doing something like this is a practice in it own right.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nIn one way or another I&rsquo;ve had a connection with this organisation for about ten years, on and off. I helped out a little bit with the previous centre, did some painting and decorating and bits and pieces there. That was about three of four years ago. I was then away working in another meditation Centre, when somebody who lives at Manor Place was on retreat there, they said that there was a possibility that a new building was going to happen in London, I didn&rsquo;t think too much about it as I was about to go travelling. When I came back to London I thought I&rsquo;ll check out the Centre and see if its happening and if they need any help. So its&rsquo; all coincided with my returning to London and needing to be here for a period of time, and being available to volunteer.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nI was working for a year for another charity, another Buddhist charity. Whilst I was paid a small amount of money I was getting used to not needing money in that place because it was totally self contained, and actually there is a little bit of that here. We are feed and housed, whilst from time to time we do go out and make use of what London has to offer, which gets expensive! But at this stage I don&rsquo;t mind that I feel content with the idea that I&rsquo;m offering time and energy too something that will be good and helpful for people in the future.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nI think it will be fantastic to see the building coming to fruition. But also it feels to me like the building has to gradually be grown into by the centre. That process I think is really interesting the organic growth into the building, as the Buddha is gradually sculpted in the main hall, and other marks are made on the Building that say; this is a Buddhist Centre now. I think that process is really interesting, it will probably be quite a long time before people can say now its finally complete.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nIf you&rsquo;ve got curtain kinds of practical skills or if you are willing to learn, we&rsquo;ve got one or two people who are highly skilled and will be able to train people. Get in touch. If you&rsquo;ve got some time and you are able to commit it consistently, that&rsquo;s important. The Centre needs people who can focus on tasks and get them done, and also really take pride in what they do, that&rsquo;s very important.','Whats it like to volunteer at Spa Road?'),(41,'Just a test please ignore',NULL,'Testing textile *content*\r\n\r\n [fMRI Scanner](image)\r\n\r\n','Leanne testing article'),(53,'Doctor of Traditional Tibetan Medicine, Working with the Tara Institute of Tibetan Medicine. Dr Soktsang is highly experienced in the field of Traditional Tibetan Medicine, having studied and practised over the past twenty years.',NULL,'Please note: Dr. Soktsang has recently changed his name from his former title of Dr. Dhonden.\r\n\r\nDr. Soktsang is highly experienced in the field of Traditional Tibetan Medicine, having studied and practised over the past twenty years.\r\n\r\nHe commenced his studies in Tibet for a period of five years under the guidance of an uncle, who was also a doctor. This enabled him to enter the Central Medical Institute for Traditional Tibetan Medicine in Lhasa, where he studied for a further five years until he graduated with the MEN-RAMPA, (Tib.) or Masters Degree of Tibetan Medicine. After graduating, he went to work at the Lhasa Mentse Khang Hospital, the premier centre of excellence of Traditional Tibetan Medicine.\r\n\r\nDuring his period there he received further teaching, instruction and transmissions from various famous Tibetan doctors, in particular from the most eminent Professor, KHENPO TSENAM, regarded by many as the greatest living practitioner and teacher in the field of Tibetan Medicine.\r\n\r\nHaving moved to India, Dr. Soktsang has not only worked at the Tibetan Medical and Astrological Institute at Dharamsala, and also at various other Centres around India, Ladakh; Shillong; Belakopi and Orrisa. Having worked in Orissa for the customary one year contract, he was particularly requested by the local people to stay on for a further period. Due to the difficult climatic conditions of that part of India, Orissa is known to be a very challenging area to work in, having as it does high levels of poverty and malaria.\r\n\r\nHe became the founder and Chief Medical Officer of the Mentse Khang Medical Institute of Orissa, India; where the Institute and his work serve the whole community.\r\n\r\nNot only is Dr. Soktsang experienced in Tibetan Medicine, but he is also a qualified practitioner of Acupuncture. He was one of the major speakers in the year 2000 at the Annual Medical Conference of Tibetan Medicine, held in Dharamsala, which is attended by Tibetan doctors from all over India and Asia. The particular theme of that conference was Diabetes.','Our_Tibetan_Doctor'),(55,'Well being at the Centre might involve a visit to the Community Clinic, a yoga class or a consolation with our visiting Tibetan Doctor. ',25,'*Thursdays*\r\n12 noon - 7pm\r\n(Unless otherwise stated) 	CranioSacral Therapy with Frederick Maitland\r\n07875 518069\r\nvcsw@mac.com\r\n\r\nIndian Head Massage / Holistic massage with Lise-Marie Lejamtel\r\n07906 362006\r\nlisemarie.lejamtel@googlemail.com\r\n\r\nPolarity Therapy / Facial Rejuvenation Massage with Zofia Hockin\r\n07951 830382\r\nzofia.hockin@talktalk.net\r\n\r\n\r\n*Fridays*\r\n9am - 7pm 	Acupuncture with Bruno Pires\r\n07563903928\r\nbrunopirez@hotmail.com\r\n\r\nCranioSacral Therapy with Frederick Maitland\r\n07875 518069\r\nvcsw@mac.com\r\n\r\nShiatsu with Imogen\r\n07545 827006\r\n\r\nChair massage / reflexology with Karin Summers\r\n07811 189529\r\nrelax@karinsummers.co.uk\r\n\r\n*Costs:* Therapies are ¬£20 for a 45 min session. The purpose of this clinic is to provide treatments to people on a low income. We encourage those who feel able to pay an additional ¬£10.\r\n\r\n*Community Clinic Cancellation Policy:* 50% of the fee will be charged if less than 24 hours notice is given directly to the therapist\r\n\r\nPlease Note: The therapies/treatments on offer are not being offered by Kagyu Samye Dzong London but the practitioner/doctor personally. Kagyu Samye Dzong London is not responsible for the treatment and accepts no liability in respect thereof.\r\n\r\nHow to find Kagyu Samye Dzong London ','Well Being'),(56,'We are so fortunate to have a wonderful centre in London, but to keep it in a way that all can enjoy and benefit from, it needs constant maintenance.',41,'We are so fortunate to have a wonderful centre in London, but to keep it in a way that all can enjoy and benefit from, it needs constant maintenance.\r\n\r\nThese are just some of the few jobs in constant need of volunteers:\r\n\r\n* Cooking\r\n* Painting\r\n* Mailings\r\n* DIY\r\n* Cleaning\r\n\r\nYou may have seen someone wandering around with a vacuum cleaner or ladder, or smelt the wonderful aromas coming from the kitchen and thought: \"I wonder how they got involved?...\" Well now is your chance to find out!\r\n\r\nCome and practice \"working meditation\" in a supportive environment either during the week or join the small group of people who spend a Saturday or Sunday a month helping out. You are guaranteed a good laugh and plenty of tea to keep you going!\r\n\r\nTalk to Lama Zangmo, one of the resident nuns or lay people the next time you are at the centre. Alternatively, contact the office, we will let you know what\'s happening!\r\n','Volunteers Needed!'),(57,'Come and join our growing team of volunteers who have already started to renovate our new building.',43,'Come and join our growing team of volunteers who have already started to renovate our new building. We have bought a grade 2 listed building which will become our permanent London centre. The building is substantially bigger than our current Manor Place centre and will require considerable renovation. \r\n\r\nWe are looking for volunteers who can commit for a length of time and we are especially keen to recruit those skilled in general building skills, painting and decorating, electrical work, plumbing, plastering, and cooking. \r\n\r\n[Spa Road Front,left,240px,180px](image)\r\n\r\nWe will have a limited amount of residential accommodation available, free-of-charge, for volunteers. If you are interested please contact the Kagyu Samye Dzong office for more details and to discuss these opportunities informally. \r\n\r\nPlease note: there are also opportunities for occasional and weekend volunteers, but please note the minimum daily time commitment is four hours. \r\n\r\n\r\nKagyu Samye Dzong London \r\n33 Manor Place \r\nLondon \r\nSE17 3BD	\r\n\r\ntel: +44 (0)20 7708 8969 \r\nemail: manorplace@samye.org','Residential Volunteer Opportunities, 2009-10: Join the Team!');
